  "prompt": "How is the NFL salary cap calculated?",
  "response": "The NFL salary cap is calculated based on a percentage of the league's total revenue, which includes money from TV contracts, ticket sales, merchandise, and other sources. Here's a basic breakdown:\n\n1. Total League Revenue Calculation\n- The NFL calculates its total revenue for the previous season\n- Approximately 48-49% of that total revenue is designated for player compensation\n\n2. Salary Cap Computation\n- The Players Association and NFL negotiate the exact percentage\n- The total revenue amount is divided by 32 (number of teams)\n- This determines the salary cap for each team for the upcoming season\n\n3. Adjustments\n- The cap can be adjusted based on factors like:\n  - Salary cap carryover from previous years\n  - Performance-based pay\n  - Specific league rules and negotiations\n\n4. Current Structure\n- As of 2023, the salary cap is around $224.8 million per team\n- Teams can manipulate their cap through techniques like restructuring contracts, signing bonuses, and contract extensions\n\n5. Salary Cap Types\n- Hard cap: Teams cannot exceed the total salary cap amount\n- Includes provisions for exceptions like injured reserve and rookie contracts\n\nThe calculation is complex and involves ongoing negotiations between the NFL and NFL Players Association.",
